            <h2>What is a Glacier?</h2>
            <p>A glacier is a large, persistent mass of ice and snow that moves over land due to gravity. It forms in regions where snow accumulation exceeds melting, sublimation, and calving. Over time, the snow compacts and turns into ice, and the glacier slowly advances or retreats depending on various environmental factors.</p>
            <p>Glaciers are large, slow-moving masses of ice that form in regions where snow accumulates over time and compacts into ice. Found in both polar regions and mountain ranges, glaciers move under their own weight, flowing like rivers of ice. As they advance and retreat, they shape the landscape, carving valleys, fjords, and other features. Glaciers are critical freshwater reservoirs, holding about 70% of Earth's fresh water, and they provide vital water supplies to millions of people. However, many glaciers are shrinking due to climate change, contributing to rising sea levels and altering ecosystems. The study of glaciers helps scientists understand past and present climate conditions.</p>
            
            <h3>About Glacier</h3>
            <p>Glaciers are massive, slow-moving bodies of ice that form when snow accumulates over time and compacts under its own weight. They are powerful natural forces that shape landscapes, create landforms, and play a crucial role in Earth's climate system.</p>
